        tabName: "World of Coffee Brussels 2026 (New)",
        title: "World of Coffee Brussels 2026: A Bold New Chapter for Kraffe Roasters",
        topImg: brusselsTopImage,
        middleImg: brusselsMiddleImage,
        introText: `
      <p class="mb-4">The global coffee community once again proved its energy and resilience at the end of June, as the Specialty Coffee Association's (SCA) <a href="https://www.worldofcoffee.org/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" class="text-orange-500 hover:text-orange-600 dark:text-orange-400 dark:hover:text-orange-300 underline"><strong>World of Coffee 2026</strong></a> brought the industry to the heart of Belgium. From 25 to 27 June, Brussels became the meeting point for roasters, producers, equipment manufacturers, and passionate coffee lovers from across the globe. For us at <a href="https://krafferoasters.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" class="text-orange-500 hover:text-orange-600 dark:text-orange-400 dark:hover:text-orange-300 underline">Kraffe Roasters</a>, this was more than just an exhibition — it was a homecoming to one of Europe's most dynamic coffee scenes, and we were thrilled to be right in the middle of it.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">The event took place at the Brussels Expo, a venue well known for hosting world-class gatherings. With two spacious halls dedicated entirely to the world of specialty coffee, the sense of scale was immediately apparent. The high attendance confirmed what we'd been feeling in the months leading up to the show: after years of virtual and hybrid events, the appetite for face-to-face connection has never been stronger.</p>
    `,
        mainContent: `
      <h2 class="mt-8 mb-4">A Venue Built for Connection</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">Visitors poured in not just from Belgium and neighbouring countries, but from all corners of Europe, transforming the halls into a lively bazaar of ideas, aromas, and freshly brewed coffee.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">For Kraffe Roasters, the journey began a day before the official opening. Our team arrived early at Hall 11, where stand number 11143 was waiting. With the help of the highly professional SCA logistics crew, our equipment was delivered promptly and positioned with care. Setting up a <a href="/products" class="text-orange-500 hover:text-orange-600 dark:text-orange-400 dark:hover:text-orange-300 underline"><strong>commercial coffee roasting machine</strong></a> on a busy exhibition floor can sometimes be a challenge, but the seamless organisation turned it into a smooth and even enjoyable experience. By the time the doors opened, our striking red 12 kg coffee roaster stood ready — a bold statement of craftsmanship and precision that would soon become a magnet for curious eyes.</p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 mb-4">Day One: The Excitement Begins</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">The first morning brought a steady stream of early visitors, all eager to explore what the exhibition had to offer. It didn't take long for our red 12 kg machine to attract its first admirers. Colours in a roasting hall often tend toward stainless steel and black, so a vibrant red drum coffee roaster naturally draws attention — and cameras. Many attendees stopped specifically to take photos, and we were more than happy to oblige. Beyond the aesthetics, however, the conversations quickly turned technical. Visitors wanted to know what made this gas coffee roaster special, and our team was ready to walk them through every detail.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">At the core of the machine's appeal is its intelligent automation. Equipped with PLC control and full Artisan compatibility, it allows roasters to monitor, adjust, and replicate profiles with absolute repeatability — a feature that resonated strongly with professionals looking to scale production without sacrificing consistency. The fact that the system is also Cropster Ready opened up another layer of discussion with tech-savvy roasters who rely on real-time data logging and roast analysis. Even on a busy show floor, the phrase "repeatability without compromise" seemed to strike a chord.</p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 mb-4">Day Two: Deepening the Dialogue</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">If the first day was about first impressions, the second was about substance. Attendance swelled noticeably, and the energy in Hall 11 reached a new pitch. The nearby competition areas erupted with applause throughout the day as baristas and brewers showcased their skills, but for us, the focus remained firmly on the art of roasting. Our team engaged in back-to-back meetings with cafe owners, micro-roastery founders, and established distributors — the vast majority from across Europe.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">One of the most rewarding aspects of the day was seeing how many conversations centred on the 12 kg model. For growing businesses, this capacity represents a sweet spot: big enough to meet the demands of a bustling cafe or small production roastery, yet compact enough to fit into a workspace without major infrastructure changes. Visitors were particularly interested in the double-wall drum construction and the fully modulating premix burner, both of which contribute to the exceptional energy efficiency and clean airflow that define our machines. Every demonstration of the cooling speed and control interface reinforced what we believe: a truly professional coffee roaster should empower its user, not overwhelm them.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">We also took note of a trend that left us genuinely surprised — the sheer number of visitors. While we had prepared for a busy show, the turnout exceeded all expectations. By the afternoon, our stand had become a constant hub of activity, with guests waiting patiently to ask questions, collect brochures, or simply watch the machine in operation. The high level of organisation meant that even during peak hours, the flow remained manageable and pleasant, a credit to the SCA team's planning.</p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 mb-4">Day Three: A Weekend Vibe with Serious Intentions</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">The final day, a Saturday, brought a more relaxed yet no less purposeful crowd. Young coffee enthusiasts mingled with seasoned industry veterans, creating a unique atmosphere that blended festival-like joy with serious business intent. For us, it was a day to solidify the connections made earlier in the week. Several promising leads turned into concrete discussions about future distribution partnerships. Although our primary audience remains commercial users, we welcomed the chance to talk about how our roasting technology scales, from a single sample roaster all the way to a full <strong>industrial coffee roaster</strong> configuration — all sharing the same philosophy of precision and control.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">Throughout the three days, we recorded approximately 75 meaningful visits to our stand. While the number might seem modest compared to consumer-facing exhibitions, the depth of these conversations was exceptional. These weren't just handshakes and business cards; they were detailed technical exchanges about airflow dynamics, gas pressure requirements, and integration with roasting software. Many guests expressed relief at finding a manufacturer willing to discuss the engineering behind a commercial coffee roasting machine with such transparency.</p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 mb-4">Looking Back, Looking Forward</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">As the closing announcements echoed through the halls and we began the careful process of packing our beloved red 12 kg roaster back into its flight case, a sense of quiet satisfaction settled over the team. The event had delivered exactly what we had hoped for: meaningful human connections, sharpened industry insight, and a renewed appreciation for the craftsmanship that drives our work.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">World of Coffee Brussels 2026 reaffirmed our commitment to participating in this flagship event year after year. The opportunity to meet new people, shake hands with long-time collaborators, and witness the passion of the coffee community first-hand is something we never take for granted. The excellent organisation, the spacious and well-laid-out halls, and the genuine warmth of the European coffee family made the three days fly by far too quickly.</p>
      <p class="mb-4">Now, our sights are set on the next destination. We are delighted to announce that Kraffe Roasters will be at World of Coffee Lisbon in 2027. The Portuguese capital, with its rich coffee culture and vibrant innovation scene, is the perfect setting for the next chapter of this journey. We look forward to bringing our machines — and the same red roaster that caused such a stir in Brussels — to a new audience next year.</p>
      <p>To everyone who visited stand 11143, took the time to learn about our approach to coffee roasting, and shared their own stories, we extend our heartfelt thanks. Your curiosity and passion are what make exhibitions like this unforgettable. If you missed us in Brussels or simply want to explore our range of commercial drum coffee roasters in more detail, we invite you to visit us at <a href="https://krafferoasters.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" class="text-orange-500 hover:text-orange-600 dark:text-orange-400 dark:hover:text-orange-300 underline">www.krafferoasters.com</a>.</p>
      <p>Thank you for being part of our story. We'll see you in Lisbon, with the machine running and the coffee fresh.</p>
    `,
